\text{To prove that the condition } \operatorname{tr}(A^k) = 0 \text{ for all } k \text{ implies that the characteristic of the field } K \text{ must be zero, we will use a proof by contradiction. Assume that } \operatorname{char}(K) = p > 0. \text{ Then, for any } k \ge 1, \text{ we have } \operatorname{tr}(A^k) \equiv 0 \pmod{p}. \text{ However, if } A = I_p, \text{ the identity matrix of size } p, \text{ then } \operatorname{tr}(A^k) = p \equiv 0 \pmod{p}, \text{ which contradicts the assumption that } A \text{ is nilpotent. Therefore, the characteristic of } K \text{ must be zero.}
\]<|im_end|>

\[
\boxed{
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Corrected Step:} \quad &\text{Assume by way of contradiction that } \operatorname{char}(K)=p>0.\\[1mm]
&\text{Then consider } A=I_p\in \mathcal{M}_p(K). \text{ For any } k\ge1, \text{ we have } \operatorname{tr}(A^k)=p\equiv0\ (\bmod\,p),\\[1mm]
&\text{so } \operatorname{tr}(A^k)=0 \text{ in } K \text{, yet } A \text{ is not nilpotent. Hence, if the condition } \operatorname{tr}(A^k)=0 \text{ for all } k\\[1mm]
&\text{implies that } A \text{ is nilpotent, we must have } \operatorname{char}(K)=0.
\end{aligned}
}
